commentText: Done that in the 80s, used 24" pipe wrenchs to put them in and occasionally a 36" manually operated single tooth, pipe tong to break them loose coming out. Doped every collar going in mostly 2000' old stripper wells.  Climb the mast and get traveling block out of lift by retrieving end hook.  So we could single line rods going back in the hole.  So hot one summer, I had to bring an electric fan to keep from overheating, glad they had a electric jack on that well, no shade and no wind blowing.  Wrenched, walked rods and pipe out one day and put it all back in the next day.  The owner drove and worked the draw works, I would stake all the guy lines with a 16lb sledgehammer that would start rolling 2" tubing if it hit a rock.  About 30 years old, and weighted 155 pounds.   .

commentText: It's not possible to complete the full Chartered Accountancy (CA) course in just one year. The CA course, including Foundation, Intermediate, and Final levels, typically takes a minimum of 4.5 to 5 years to complete. This includes the required articleship training period of three years. Even for graduates entering through the direct entry route, the minimum duration is 4.5 years.  Here's a more detailed breakdown:  Foundation Level: 6 months Intermediate Level: 8-10 months Articleship Training: 3 years Final Level: 6-12 months While some students might be able to accelerate their studies by studying intensely, passing exams quickly, and potentially completing the final level in one year after clearing the intermediate level, this would be an exception rather than the norm. commentText: My dad was chronically ill at the end of his life. We were so thankful for the food service and cleaning teams at the hospital he was regularly at. Food service always delivered with a smile and didn't blink an eye when my dad ordered some slightly odd combinations. When my dad was feeling well enough to enjoy his food, he looked forward to certain dishes, and swore that the hospital had the best French toast he'd ever had. The main cleaner we had. was a mild-mannered middle-aged man. On one particularly... messy day, we apologized to the cleaner. "Don't worry. Before this, I used to work on a farm. Humans are nowhere near as bad as cows."

videoTitle: What Is Hospital Food Really Like? Feeding Hundreds of Patients a Day | On the Job | NYT Cooking

commentText: as a healthcare worker, i totally understand the critiques of hospital food, a lot of hospitals (in the US especially) need a total overhaul of their menu/offerings. (aka, healthier more balanced options, not always easy when cooking mostly bland food on a massive scale)  but the chefs in the cafeteria (who cook for both patients and employees/doctors & nurses etc. who eat 1, 2, or even 3 meals or more per shift at the hospital), and the custodial/sanitation staff are the absolute backbones of any hospital. absolutely nothing could get done in any hospital without them. big shout out to chef bill.

videoTitle: What Is Hospital Food Really Like? Feeding Hundreds of Patients a Day | On the Job | NYT Cooking
videoDescription: Hospital food: Is it really as bad as we're supposed to think it is? Meet Bill, a hot cook at the University of Pittsburgh Medical ...
commentText: After a 36 hour induction with my first baby, and pushing for over 3 hours, I was so exhausted. I'd had no food and almost no sleep for that whole time. The 2 English muffin breakfast sandwiches with bacon, egg, and cheese + the chocolate milk that I had for my first meal post-childbirth will live forever in my memory as one of the best meals I've ever eaten, period. I've had pastries in Paris and pasta in Rome, but that breakfast is Proustian. Thanks to Bill and to all the other Bills out there caring for patients in this way.

commentText: I usually don't comment videos on YouTube in general, but this really hits home for me! As a person who worked as a CNA for 18 years,  I am so happy that hospital cooks are finally getting their recognition!  For patients and staff, they are our lifelines and morale boosters, especially the healthcare staff  who works nightshift. As healthcare workers, we often either forget to bring our own lunch or we're too busy to prep food at home, they can make or break a shift especially on nights when there are really no restaurants around that are open in the middle of the night.  If me and my coworkers know that one of our favorite cooks is in the kitchen, then chances are we are going to have really good night shift. To all my healthcare workers (Doctors, nurses, RTs, PTs, CNAs, Techs, etc.), please be kind to your hospital kitchen staff, especially on nightshift. They know they can't always work on our schedule and they also understand that you priorities are the patients. Treat them right and I promise you,  they will take care  of you because  the hospital cooks are also  our healthcare workers!

commentText: Thank you for covering Hospital Kitchens and food service. I worked in a Hospital cafeteria, and a lot of people don't know what goes on behind the scenes.  The staff are doing their best and they work VERY hard. Some of the cooks in my Hospital would sometimes stay HOURS late to help finish meals for the patients, and then come back the next morning. Sometimes we would only have one cook for the entire Hospital, sometimes stuff breaks and certain foods can't be made, depending on the patients sometimes you have to pull a supervisor to sign off on a tray make sure the meal is prepped correctly, it's a lot. Staff in other positions sometimes look down on kitchen and cafeteria workers, so I hope this helps people understand how hard they work to feed everyone.

commentText: I wish that we had tweaked the incentives around capital and labor years ago. We punish labor (tax it) and reward capital (many ways to park capital and avoid taxes) and have allowed capital to accumulate to the point where Elon Musk could build xAI from scratch and create the largest AI cluster in the world in about a year. When capital makes labor all-but-obsolete, the tax base is gone, people have no way to earn a living and bad things that we can't yet imagine may come to pass. The Gini scores will approach 1 and society will struggle to hold together.

It's a sense of community you won't find in any modern American suburb.

commentText: Just to make things clear, what companies are calling AI now, is just LLM (Large Language model) that is good at mimic human writing. Like your autocorrect keyboard but is trained at every text that has ever been written, not just your text messages. However, it really doesn't understand what is saying, it is almost like a parrot, just because it repeats what you say it doesn't mean the parrot understand what it is saying. Whether LLMs or diffusion model or image/video generation, don't understand the world, they don't understand physics, they don't understand chemistry or biology. They are just good at mimicking what is has been trained on. That doesn't mean that they are not useful, but at it's core it just mimicking what it saw with some randomness sprinkled on top to it doesn't end up repeating everything it saw word for word.

commentText: While AI tools can be helpful for certain development tasks, claims of 75% productivity increases likely don't reflect the reality of most software engineering teams working on complex, real-world applications. Simple projects might see bigger gains, but enterprise software development involves much more than just writing code. It's worth noting that AI assistants are tools that augment human work rather than replace human judgment and expertise. They can speed up some tasks like boilerplate code generation or debugging, but they don't independently "think" or understand context the way humans do. They're pattern-matching systems that work best with clear instructions. The relationship between AI coding tools and business outcomes like sales isn't straightforward either. Even if developers write code faster, that doesn't automatically translate to more revenueâ€”product-market fit, user experience, and business strategy still matter most. Better prompts definitely improve AI outputs, but they're not a magic solution. The quality of results still depends heavily on the problem's complexity, the human's expertise in reviewing and integrating the output, and realistic expectations about what these tools can and cannot do.

commentText: I want to make one correction to the lady around 9:17. The word you're looking for is "automated tracking system" or ATS. Examples include Workday and Talio. These are not new and as a 32 year old when I graduated when I was younger I encountered them as well (circa 2015-2016). ATS systems have nothing to do with the impact ChatGPT and generative AI has on the labour market and it's not helpful to confuse the two. People have been complaining about ATS systems for a very long time, even before ChatGPT and the like existed. The time when humans would review applications was a very long time ago, like maybe 2010 or thereabouts.

AI has generally underperformed everywhere it's been implemented, with studies generally showing it makes workers less efficient (which the media should know, considering the high-profile embarrassments they've had). As the for the hype, it's largely driven by a mix of speculation, advertising/marketing, and bad assumptions about generative AI's current capabilities. All that said, the reporter(s) and pundit(s) for this story could easily lose their jobs to AI without anything of value being lost because their claims involve as much hallucination and shoddy information as AI.

commentText: Ex-truck driver here.   I drove Cents Per Mile, owner operator and lease operator. OTR.   It not very profitable.   -owner operator. If you buy a brand new truck, your expenses go towards the truck payment, trailer payment (which is another expense), insurance for both truck and trailer, insurance for the loads, fuel for both truck and trailer, IFTA,  Tolls (east coast tolls are absurdly expensive) . Plus,  repair schedules. Also, depends highly on what the market offers and other factors. Sure, you can earn 350k - 450k gross per year. BUT, with all of those expenses  you will net under 60k per year. And then you're taxed on personal income.  If you buy USED equipment, the same as above applies, except now there are major pending issues, repairs, and preventive  maintenance. Your equipment will become a risk factor. -Cpm (cent per mile) you can earn 50-75 cents per mile, but most  if not all, companies have you running from zipcode to zipcode basis instead of per mile. You have no control on maintenance and no control on basically anything. And then escrow gets removed, also, personal tax at 33%.  -lease operator is almost a hybrid of both owner and CPM, just depending of the clauses being signed for at the beginning of your contract agreements.  The only and best way to make good money is if you own a company and have everyone else work for you,  take no executive decisions with 200+ trucks, have your own shop, have your own insurance firm and have PRISTINE, loyal and fully dedicated drivers under your belt. But, that is just a dream.

For most local jobs though I would say expect to make around 60-80k and if hauling hazmat maybe up to 100k or decently more depending on area. Still better than a lot and more than enough to live on depending on your area.  You could also work for a mega carrier (Big Fleet companies like Swift, CR England, knight, etc.) and eventually become a trainer. Now, all of a suden, you are able to administrate (in a more efficient way) your own business. You probably was able to make this list, because of your knowledge about finalcial and economics terms... the ones you learn by studying accounting.. commentText: Before I could start Rover, I had to meet someone in a rented office to see how I put on harnesses. Maybe things changed? They also ask for references, I think 3. If you plan on doing it I suggest Rover over Wag. With Wag, you often don't know what you might be getting into with the dog. They changed things a bit so you can see and know more now, but other problems like door codes not being given/how to get into the building. Really awkward to have to wait for someone to come out so you can come in because the owner wouldn't leave the door code or a key. When you start out on Wag you'll likely have to walk dogs others don't want to walk, strong and stubborn, or high energy, or late at night.
